Identity is foundational to the achievement of personal sovereignty and the kernel of voting systems. Today’s standard identity systems are based on certifications provided by a central authority where users are forced to share private information risking identity theft if authorities gets hacked. Votes (on any system) are valid if and only if membership is verified within an organization, no democracy can run on corrupted identities. Therefore [http://sovereign.software Sovereign] is organization-centric as a technology, unless the identity verification process of an organization becomes decentralized.

[[File:/images/identity-blockchain.png|Self-sovereign Identity.]]

Democracy Earth Foundation will grant ''VOTE'' tokens using a decentralized social and algorithmic protocol for identity known as ''Proof of Identity'', where verified participants in the network can use their allocated ''VOTEs'' to validate (or not) new identities. Using a Bitcoin analogy: ''VOTEs'' get mined with a decentralized identity verification process instead of a decentralized transaction verification process. Rather than harnessing ''distributed computing power'' decrypting transactions, this process uses ''distributed attention power'' that verifies a user's self-generated evidence stating his or her own identity.

A well known precedent of attention mining are CAPTCHA tests often found in the login of high-traffic websites. CAPTCHA is an acronym for ''Completetly Automated Public Turing test to tell Computers and Humans Apart''. These consist of simple vision excercises that can be completed by a human more easily than by a computer. A field [https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~biglou/reCAPTCHA_Science.pdf pioneered by researcher Louis Von Ahn], where he used this technique to help build datasets able to train machine learning algorithms capable of reading printed words. As a Google engineer Von Ahn created a simple test distributed across all login pages that displayed two words obtained from scanned pictures. A user would write both words in a text input field to prove he is human and not a machine. The system already knows the meaning of the first word (hence validating the user is human) but it gets trained with the second input as it uses this information to further optimize its character recognition algorithms. This simple excercise has been extended to train all kinds of pattern recognition systems and it contributed to the security of websites preventing bots (and botnets) from intruding.

Attention can also serve as the computational foundation to validate human identities on a decentralized network similar to [https://bitcoin.com/bitcoin.pdf Bitcoin's Proof of Work algorithm (POW)] used by mining nodes to timestamp peer to peer transactions. Bitcoin is able to synchronize its network without central authorities by rewarding miners that contribute computing capacity to verify the validity of blocks containing transactions. Each miner generates a POW hash per block that meets a difficulty target shared across the network. If 51% of the nodes in the network accept the verified block, it gets chained to the blockchain and the miner starts working on the next transaction block using the accepted block as the previous hash. This technique permits monetary transactions without banks. A democracy without governments can work the same way but instead of verifying encrypted blocks, human attention serves the purpose to validate ''VOTE'' holders.

