Recent developments in distributed computing are allowing the rise of  truly self-sovereign identity systems. Asymmetric cryptography ensures security from the user perspective, and trust between peers can arise in a decentralised manner, with the collection of credentials and reputation management. Because anyone can use these identities and the resulting benefits without an intervening authority, they’re called “self-sovereign.”

With trust itself being enabled by technologies and not institutions, the next evolution of the Internet will be the creation of a common identity layer that allows people, organisations and things to have their own self-sovereign identity that is secure, under their control, and always available to them, with no need for intermediary permissions.

